./.title: Introduction
./.body:
AWS SysOps Practice
The goal of this repo is to contain exercise code generated while training for AWS SysOps certification. Exercises will be mined from various sources.
There will most likely be overlap in exercises.
Quizlet
I created a quizlet AWS folder to store flashcards for AWS related vocabulary and to ask/answer review questions.
If you are interested in using these, navigate to My AWS Quizlet Folder and study!
Gitbook
Building this documentation was done using gitbook, build on Node. If you would like to contribute (or you are the original author and have forgotten how to run/build this), install node (via NVM, perhaps?) and run npm install to install project dependencies. To serve files locally, run npm start. Once satisfied, build files to GitPages friendly /docs folder by running npm run build to generate relevant files.
To see results on git page, navigate to aallbrig.github.io/aws-sysops-practice

sysops-admin-associate-study-guide-2018/.title: Chapter 4 Compute
sysops-admin-associate-study-guide-2018/.body:
Chapter 4 Compute
Exercise 4.1 Create a Linux Instance via AWS Management Console
Up

Launch EC2
Choose Linux AMI
T.2 micro instance type (free tier eligible)
Launch into default VPC
Assign a public IP address
Add tag to instance of key = Yankee, value = Zulu
Create new security group called YankeeZuluSG
Add rule to YankeeZulu security group that allows SSH access from anywhere (0.0.0.0/0)
Launch instance
Create new key pair, name it YankeeZuluKeyPair, save private portion
SSH into instance
You may need to chmod 400 the newly downloaded keypair


Install software updates
Maybe you want to start a simple web server; assuming Ubuntu OS...
Add HTTP inbound rule to YankeeZuluSG from anywhere
mkdir www && cd www
touch index.html
Run... cat  index.html
 
   Test HTML page
   Test HTML page
 
 HEREDOC


sudo python3 -m http.server 80


Run ifconfig -a then make note of IP address
Access instance metadata by running curl http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/public-ipv4
Exist SSH session

Down
If not using for Exercise 4.6

Terminate instance
Delete security group called YankeeZuluSG
Delete keypair YankeeZuluKeyPair

Exercise 4.2 Create a Windows Instance via AWS Management Console
Up

Launch EC2
Choose Windows 2016 Base AMI
The book wants T2.medium, but that isn't free tier so... t2.micro it is! Let's see how well the t2.micro handles RDP
Launch into default VPC
Assign public IP address
Add tag to instance of key = alpha, value = bravo
Create new security group called AlphaBravoSG
Add rule to security group that allows RDP from anywhere (0.0.0.0/0)
Launch instance
Create new key pair, name it AlphaBravoKeyPair
You may need to chmod 400 the newly downloaded keypair


On connect instance UI, decrypt administrator password, then download the RDP file
Connect to instance and poke around for a bit

Down

Terminate instance
Delete security group called AlphaBravoSG
Delete key pair called AlphaBravoKeyPair

Exercise 4.3 Create Linux Instance via AWS CLI
Up
Before starting, take note of AMI ID for the target region.

Set variables IMAGE_AMI= \
 KEY_NAME= \
 SECURITY_GROUP_ID= \
 SUBNET_ID=


Run the command... aws ec2 run-instances \
 --image-id $IMAGE_AMI \
 --count 1 \
 --instance-type t2.micro \
 --key-name $KEY_NAME \
 --security-group-ids $SECURITY_GROUP_ID \
 --subnet-id $SUBNET_ID


SSH into instance, poke around a bit

Down

You may need to run aws ec2 describe-instances to get instance IDs
 aws ec2 describe-instances | jq ".Reservations[].Instances[].InstanceId" -r can be used if jq is installed

Once instance ID has been identified, run aws ec2 terminate-instances --instance-ids and fill in instance ID value
Handy one liner, to terminate all currently running EC2 instances aws ec2 describe-instances \
 | jq ".Reservations[].Instances[].InstanceId" -r \
 | xargs -n1 -I instance_id aws ec2 terminate-instances --instance-ids instance_id


If needed, delete security group and key pair if one was dedicated to this exercise

Exercise 4.4 Create a Windows Instance via AWS CLI
Up

Set variables IMAGE_AMI="ami-0b7b74ba8473ec232" \
 VPC_ID=$( \
   aws ec2 describe-vpcs | jq -c ".Vpcs | map(select(.IsDefault | contains(true)))[].VpcId" -r \
 ) \
 SG_NAME=AlphaBravoSG \
 SG_DESCRIPTION="Security Group for Alpha Bravo"
 KEY_NAME=AlphaBravoKP \
 SUBNET_ID=$(
   aws ec2 describe-subnets --filters "Name=vpc-id,Values=$VPC_ID" | jq ".Subnets[] | .SubnetId" -r | gshuf | head -n 1 \
 ) \
 SECURITY_GROUP_ID=$( \
   aws ec2 describe-security-groups | jq ".SecurityGroups | map(select(.GroupName | contains(\"$SG_NAME\")))[] .GroupId" -r \
 )


Identify if you already have relevant security group
 aws ec2 describe-security-groups | jq ".SecurityGroups | map(select(.GroupName | contains(\"$SG_NAME\")))[]"

 Above will return an object or nothing. If nothing, the security group does not exist.

If no security group exists, run... aws ec2 create-security-group --group-name $SG_NAME \
 --description $SG_DESCRIPTION \
 --vpc-id $VPC_ID


Assign security group ID to variable SECURITY_GROUP_ID=$(aws ec2 describe-security-groups | jq ".SecurityGroups | map(select(.GroupName | contains(\"$SG_NAME\")))[] .GroupId" -r)


Create ingress rule for RDP from anywhere (0.0.0.0/0) aws ec2 authorize-security-group-ingress \
 --group-id $SECURITY_GROUP_ID \
 --protocol tcp \
 --port 3389 \
 --cidr 0.0.0.0/0




Identify if you already have relevant key pair aws ec2 describe-key-pairs --key-name $KEY_NAME


If you do not, run aws ec2 create-key-pair --key-name $KEY_NAME  --query 'KeyMaterial' --output text > "${KEY_NAME}.pem"




Run the command... aws ec2 run-instances \
 --image-id $IMAGE_AMI \
 --count 1 \
 --instance-type t2.micro \
 --key-name $KEY_NAME \
 --security-group-ids $SECURITY_GROUP_ID \
 --subnet-id $SUBNET_ID


RDP into instance, poke around a bit

Down

You may need to run aws ec2 describe-instances to get instance IDs
 aws ec2 describe-instances | jq ".Reservations[].Instances[].InstanceId" -r can be used if jq is installed

Once instance ID has been identified, run aws ec2 terminate-instances --instance-ids and fill in instance ID value
Handy one liner, to terminate all currently running EC2 instances aws ec2 describe-instances \
 | jq ".Reservations[].Instances[].InstanceId" -r \
 | xargs -n1 -I instance_id aws ec2 terminate-instances --instance-ids instance_id


If needed, delete security group and key pair if one was dedicated to this exercise aws ec2 delete-key-pair --key-name $KEY_NAME
 aws ec2 delete-security-group --group-id $SECURITY_GROUP_ID



Exercise 4.5 Inspect AWS Service Health Dashboards
Up

Go to http://status.aws.amazon.com and poke around a bit
Go to http://phd.aws.amazon.com and poke around a bitDown

Log out of console

Exercise 4.6 Use Elastic IP Address
Up

Use existing or spin up new EC2 instance (Ubuntu Server)

Assign variables IMAGE_AMI="ami-04169656fea786776" \
 VPC_ID=$( \
   aws ec2 describe-vpcs | jq -c ".Vpcs | map(select(.IsDefault | contains(true)))[].VpcId" -r \
 ) \
 SG_NAME=YankeeZuluSG \
 SG_DESCRIPTION="Security Group for Yankee Zulu"
 KEY_NAME=YankeeZuluKP \
 SUBNET_ID=$(
   aws ec2 describe-subnets --filters "Name=vpc-id,Values=$VPC_ID" | jq ".Subnets[] | .SubnetId" -r | gshuf | head -n 1 \
 ) \
 SECURITY_GROUP_ID=$( \
   aws ec2 describe-security-groups | jq ".SecurityGroups | map(select(.GroupName | contains(\"$SG_NAME\")))[] .GroupId" -r \
 )


Identify or create security group

If none already exist
 aws ec2 create-security-group --group-name $SG_NAME \
 --description $SG_DESCRIPTION \
 --vpc-id $VPC_ID


Assign newly created security group ID to variable SECURITY_GROUP_ID=$(aws ec2 describe-security-groups | jq ".SecurityGroups | map(select(.GroupName | contains(\"$SG_NAME\")))[] .GroupId" -r)


Create ingress rule for SSH from anywhere (0.0.0.0/0) aws ec2 authorize-security-group-ingress \
 --group-id $SECURITY_GROUP_ID \
 --protocol tcp \
 --port 22 \
 --cidr 0.0.0.0/0




Identify or create key pair

If none already exist
 aws ec2 create-key-pair --key-name $KEY_NAME  --query 'KeyMaterial' --output text > "${KEY_NAME}.pem"


Ensure proper permissions exist on newly created .pem file chmod 400 "${KEY_NAME}.pem"




Spin up EC2 instance aws ec2 run-instances \
 --image-id $IMAGE_AMI \
 --count 1 \
 --instance-type t2.micro \
 --key-name $KEY_NAME \
 --security-group-ids $SECURITY_GROUP_ID \
 --subnet-id $SUBNET_ID


Assign instance ID to variable INSTANCE_ID=$(aws ec2 describe-instances | jq '.Reservations[].Instances[].InstanceId' -r)

 TODO: Above two commands could be combined


Make note of it's public IP address. This will be changed in later instructions
Run this command to identify EC2 instance public IP address


Allocate new Elastic IP address, if none exist
 aws ec2 allocate-address --domain vpc

 ALLOCATION_ID=$(aws ec2 describe-addresses | jq '.Addresses[].AllocationId' -r)

 TODO: Above steps could probably be combined into one command. One can take the output of the create command and pipe into a variable.

Associate it to your EC2 instance aws ec2 associate-address --instance-id $INSTANCE_ID --allocation-id $ALLOCATION_ID


SSH into your EC2 instance from the elastic IP address (this will be different than previous "identify default public address of EC2 instance" step)

Down

Disassociate elastic IP address
Release elastic IP address
Terminate EC2 instance
Remove security group and key pair

Exercise 4.7 Work with Metadata
Up

Launch EC2 instance
Run command curl http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data to see meta data
Add onto above curl command to see more information e.g. curl http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/security-groups
 curl http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/public-ipv4



Down

Close down EC2 instance and any new security groups or keypairs for this exercise

sysops-admin-associate-study-guide-2018/.title: Chapter 5 Networking
sysops-admin-associate-study-guide-2018/.body:
Chapter 5 Networking
Exercise 5.1 Create an Elastic IP
Up

Allocate Elastic IP address
 aws ec2 allocate-address


Make note of IP address
 aws ec2 describe-addresses | jq '.Addresses[].PublicIp'



Down

Disassociate Elastic IP address
 # Identify allocation ID
 aws ec2 describe-addresses
 # Disassociate address
 aws ec2 disassociate-address


Release Elastic IP address # Identify allocation ID
 aws ec2 describe-addresses
 # Release address
 aws ec2 release-address --allocation-id



Exercise 5.2a Create VPC from management console
Up

Start the VPC wizard from VPC section in AWS management console
Select "VPC with public and private subnets"
Name VPC "VPC-1" and cidr block of 10.0.0.16
Assign public cidr block of 10.0.0.0/24 and no preference on availability zone
Assign private cidr block of 10.0.1.0/24 and no preference on availability zone
Assign NAT gateway and use the elastic IP address from Exercise 5.1
Assign an S3 endpoint and leave default DNS and tenancy options

Down

In "Your VPCs" section, find your VPC, select it,  and execute "Actions>Delete VPC"

Exercise 5.2b Create VPC from AWS CLI
Up

Create VPC and assign ID to variable
 VPC_ID=$(aws ec2 create-vpc --cidr-block 10.0.0.0/16 --query 'Vpc.VpcId' --output text)


Create public subnet

Create a subnet
 PUBLIC_SUBNET_ID=$(aws ec2 create-subnet --vpc-id $VPC_ID --cidr-block 10.0.0.0/24 --query 'Subnet.SubnetId' --output text)


Create internet gateway
 INTERNET_GATEWAY_ID=$(aws ec2 create-internet-gateway --query 'InternetGateway.InternetGatewayId' --output text)


Attach internet gateway to VPC
 aws ec2 attach-internet-gateway --vpc-id $VPC_ID --internet-gateway-id $INTERNET_GATEWAY_ID


Create custom route table for VPC
 ROUTE_TABLE_ID=$(aws ec2 create-route-table --vpc-id $VPC_ID --query 'RouteTable.RouteTableId' --output text)


Create route that points all traffic to internet gateway
 aws ec2 create-route \
 --route-table-id $ROUTE_TABLE_ID \
 --gateway-id $INTERNET_GATEWAY_ID \
 --destination-cidr-block 0.0.0.0/0

 Confirm the desired route exists by running...
 aws ec2 describe-route-tables --route-table-id $ROUTE_TABLE_ID


Associate subnet with route table
 aws ec2 associate-route-table --subnet-id $PUBLIC_SUBNET_ID --route-table-id $ROUTE_TABLE_ID


Map public IP on launch when launching into public subnet
 aws ec2 modify-subnet-attribute --subnet-id $PUBLIC_SUBNET_ID --map-public-ip-on-launch


(Test) Create EC2 instance in newly created VPC and verify internet access

Create keypair, if needed
 KEY_NAME=TestTangoKP

 aws ec2 create-key-pair --key-name $KEY_NAME --query 'KeyMaterial' --output text > "${KEY_NAME}.pem"

 chmod 400 "${KEY_NAME}.pem"


Create security group and SSH ingress rule, if needed
 SECURITY_GROUP_ID=$(aws ec2 create-security-group --vpc-id $VPC_ID --group-name TestTangoSG --description "SSH access for TestTango instance." --query 'GroupId' --output text)

 aws ec2 authorize-security-group-ingress --group-id $SECURITY_GROUP_ID --protocol tcp --port 22 --cidr 0.0.0.0/0


Launch instance into public subnet
 INSTANCE_ID=$(aws ec2 run-instances --image-id ami-04169656fea786776  --count 1 --instance-type t2.micro --key-name TestTangoKP --security-group-ids $SECURITY_GROUP_ID --subnet-id $PUBLIC_SUBNET_ID --query 'Instances[0].InstanceId' --output text)


SSH into instance and verify internet access




Create private subnet
 PRIVATE_SUBNET_ID=$(aws ec2 create-subnet --vpc-id $VPC_ID --cidr-block 10.0.1.0/24 --query 'Subnet.SubnetId' --output text)

Down

Terminate test EC2 instance, if applicable
 aws ec2 terminate-instances --instance-ids $INSTANCE_ID


Delete security group
 aws ec2 delete-security-group --group-id $SECURITY_GROUP_ID


Delete key pair
 aws ec2 delete-key-pair --key-name $KEY_NAME

 If located in same directory, remove the key pair's ".pem" file too
 rm "${KEY_NAME}.pem"


Delete subnets (public, private)
 aws ec2 delete-subnet --subnet-id $PRIVATE_SUBNET_ID

 aws ec2 delete-subnet --subnet-id $PUBLIC_SUBNET_ID


Delete custom route table
 aws ec2 delete-route-table --route-table-id $ROUTE_TABLE_ID


Detach internet gateway from VPC
 aws ec2 detach-internet-gateway --internet-gateway-id $INTERNET_GATEWAY_ID --vpc-id $VPC_ID


Delete internet gateway
 aws ec2 delete-internet-gateway --internet-gateway-id $INTERNET_GATEWAY_ID


Delete VPC
 aws ec2 delete-vpc --vpc-id $VPC_ID



Exercise 5.3 Tag Your VPC and Subnets
Up

Spin up a new VPC, with private & public subnet from exercise 5.2b
Through AWS management console (because piecing together ARNs is a beast), find your VPC and tag it
Through AWS management console, find your VPC's subnets and tag them

Down

Delete tags from your VPC
Spin down your VPC, private & public subnet

Exercise 5.4, 5.5, 5.6, 5.7 Create an Elastic Network Interface (ENI), associate EIP with ENI, test ENI, delete VPC
Up

Spin up a new VPC, with private subnet, public subnet, and EC2 instance from exercise 5.2b
Create a network interface; use your VPC's public subnet and use a security group (default or new)
 NETWORK_INTERFACE_ID=$(aws ec2 create-network-interface --groups $SECURITY_GROUP_ID --subnet-id $PUBLIC_SUBNET_ID --query 'NetworkInterface.NetworkInterfaceId' --output text)


Tag your ENI via AWS management console
Create Elastic IP address
 ALLOCATION_ID=$(aws ec2 allocate-address --query AllocationId --output text)


Associate EIP to ENI
 ASSOCIATION_ID=$(aws ec2 associate-address --allocation-id $ALLOCATION_ID --network-interface-id $NETWORK_INTERFACE_ID --query 'AssociationId' --output text)


Attach network interface to EC2 instance
 ATTACHMENT_ID=$(aws ec2 attach-network-interface --network-interface-id $NETWORK_INTERFACE_ID --instance-id $INSTANCE_ID --device-index 1 --query 'AttachmentId' --output text)

Down

Delete your tag through AWS management console (optional, as the resources are being deleted)
Detach ENI resource from EC2 instance aws ec2 detach-network-interface --attachment-id $ATTACHMENT_ID


Disassociate EIP from ENI aws ec2 disassociate-address --association-id $ASSOCIATION_ID


Release your Elastic IP aws ec2 release-address --allocation-id $ALLOCATION_ID


Delete ENI resource aws ec2 delete-network-interface --network-interface-id $NETWORK_INTERFACE_ID


Spin down VPC following 5.2b Down instructions

sysops-admin-associate-study-guide-2018/.title: Chapter 6 Storage Systems
sysops-admin-associate-study-guide-2018/.body:
Chapter 6 Storage Systems
Exercise 6.1a Create an Encrypted EBS Volume (using management console)
Up

Navigate to EC2 > Elastic Block Store > Volumes
Create volume
Select default KMS master key. Create one if none exist

Down

Delete volume
Delete KMS key, if one was created for exercise

Exercise 6.1b Create an Encrypted EBS Volume (using AWS CLI)
Up

Create new KMS key KEY_ID=$(aws kms create-key --query 'KeyMetadata.KeyId' --output text)


Create new KMS alias, associate with newly created KMS key
 ALIAS_NAME="alias/aallbrig/chapter-exercises-ebs"

 aws kms create-alias --alias-name $ALIAS_NAME --target-key-id $KEY_ID


Get a random availability zone (assuming you're on OSX and have installed coreutils, and have shuf under gshuf) AVAILABILITY_ZONE=$(gshuf -n 1 -e $(aws ec2 describe-availability-zones --query 'AvailabilityZones[].ZoneName' --output text))


Create encrypted EBS volume VOLUME_ID=$(aws ec2 create-volume --availability-zone $AVAILABILITY_ZONE --encrypted --kms-key-id $KEY_ID --size 1 --volume-type standard --query 'VolumeId' --output text)


Celebrate. No really, the book's exercise doesn't ask you to do more with the encrypted volume.

Down

Delete volume aws ec2 delete-volume --volume-id $VOLUME_ID


Delete alias aws kms delete-alias --alias-name $ALIAS_NAME


Schedule KMS key to be deleted aws kms schedule-key-deletion --key-id $KEY_ID --pending-window-in-days 7



Exercise 6.2 Monitor EBS using CloudWatch
Up

Open CloudWatch service dashboard in management console and navigate to EBS per-volume metrics aws cloudwatch list-metrics --namespace "AWS/EBS" --max-items 10


Poke around, explore aws cloudwatch help



Down
N/A because no resources were created, thus no resources need to be destroyed
Exercise 6.3 Create and attach an EFS volume
Up

Launch EC2 instance (preferably linux ami)
Open EFS service dashboard and create file system
Log in to console of linux instance, install NFS client on EC2 instance sudo yum install -y nfs-utils


Make directory for newly created EFS mkdir efs


Mount the newly created file system using DNS name sudo mount -t nfs4 -o nfscers=4.1,rsize=1048576,wsize=1048576,hard,timeo=600,retrans=2 $EFS_DNS / efs



Down

Terminate EC2 instance
Delete EFS file system

Exercise 6.4 Create and use S3 bucket
Up

Create globally unique name for S3 bucket RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME="test-bucket-$(openssl rand -hex 18)"


Create S3 bucket aws s3 mb "s3://${RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME}"


Test S3 bucket

Create random file to upload echo "Test S3 bucket upload\!" > test.txt


Upload file to newly created S3 bucket aws s3 cp test.txt "s3://${RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME}/test.txt" --acl public-read


Verify upload by listing out contents of bucket aws s3 ls "s3://${RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME}"


Check public read permission via cURL
 curl "https://s3.amazonaws.com/$RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME/test.txt"


If you want to verify public access by restricting access, follow these next commands
  aws s3 cp test.txt "s3://${RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME}/test.txt" --acl private
  curl "https://s3.amazonaws.com/$RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME/test.txt"

  You will see a generic "access denied" HTML page



Delete local test.txt file rm test.txt


Download text.txt file from S3 bucket aws s3 cp "s3://${RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME}/test.txt" test.txt





Down

Remove test file (if created for testing purposes) rm test.txt


Recursively remove all content in bucket aws s3 rm "s3://${RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME}" --recursive


Delete s3 bucket aws s3api delete-bucket --bucket "${RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME}"



Exercise 6.5 Enable S3 versioning
Up

If you do not already have a bucket, follow the steps for exercise 6.4
Enable S3 bucket versioning aws s3api put-bucket-versioning --bucket $RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME --versioning-configuration Status=Enabled


Get a baseline on versions aws s3api list-object-versions --bucket $RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME

 Notice that there is only one version
Write a new version of test.txt to test versioning echo "Test S3 bucket upload\! Version 2" > test.txt


Upload new version of test.txt to S3 bucket aws s3 cp test.txt "s3://${RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME}/test.txt"


Check versions-- you should see a new listing after uploading your new version of test.txt aws s3api list-object-versions --bucket $RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME





Down

Follow steps for 6.4 to spin down bucket

Exercise 6.6 Enable cross-region replication
Up

Create globally unique names for two S3 buckets RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME_A="test-bucket-$(openssl rand -hex 18)"
 RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME_B="test-bucket-$(openssl rand -hex 18)"


Create both buckets but in different regions aws s3 mb "s3://${RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME_A}" --region us-west-2
 aws s3 mb "s3://${RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME_B}" --region us-east-1


Enable S3 bucket versioning aws s3api put-bucket-versioning --bucket $RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME_A --versioning-configuration Status=Enabled
 aws s3api put-bucket-versioning --bucket $RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME_B --versioning-configuration Status=Enabled


Do the rest through management console; configure the source bucket (A) to replicate to a destination bucket (B). The form will allow you to create a new IAM role, which is required for this functionality.

Down

Delete buckets via AWS management console.

Exercise 6.7 Create a Glacier Vault
Up

Create random vault name VAULT_NAME="test-vault-$(openssl rand -hex 18)"


Create vault, using - to signify your account ID aws glacier create-vault --acount-id - --vault-name $VAULT_NAME



Down

Remove vault aws glacier delete-vault --account-id - --vault-name $VAULT_NAME



Exercise 6.8 Enable Lifecycle Rules
Up

Create S3 bucket, if you do not have one already
Create .json file with a "move to glacier" lifecycle rule. I created mine inside ch6/s3-life-cycle-config.json directory/file. {
   "Rules": [
     {
       "ID": "Move to Glacier after thirty days",
       "Prefix": "cold_storage/",
       "Status": "Enabled",
       "Transition": {
         "Days": 30,
         "StorageClass": "GLACIER"
       }
     }
   ]
 }


Apply lifecycle configuration aws s3api put-bucket-lifecycle --bucket $RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME --lifecycle-configuration file://ch6/s3-life-cycle-config.json


Verify lifecycle rule has been applied aws s3api get-bucket-lifecycle-configuration --bucket $RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME



Down

Delete lifecycle rule from bucket aws s3api delete-bucket-lifecycle --bucket $RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME


Delete S3 bucket, if one was created

sysops-admin-associate-study-guide-2018/.title: Chapter 7 Databases
sysops-admin-associate-study-guide-2018/.body:
Chapter 7 Databases
Exercise 7.1 Create a New Option Group
Up

Set option group name variable and create option group for... Hmmm, MySQL... And the current latest version at time of writing is 5.7
 OPTION_GROUP_NAME="test-option-group-$(openssl rand -hex 18)"

 aws rds create-option-group --option-group-name $OPTION_GROUP_NAME --engine-name mysql --major-engine-version 5.7 --option-group-description $(openssl rand -hex 64)



Down

Delete option group aws rds delete-option-group --option-group-name $OPTION_GROUP_NAME



Exercise 7.2 Create a DynamoDB Table
Up

Create input JSON for table definition. I named my file create-dynamo-db-table.json and put inside ch7 directory. {
     "AttributeDefinitions": [
         {
             "AttributeName": "Artist",
             "AttributeType": "S"
         },
         {
             "AttributeName": "Title",
             "AttributeType": "S"
         }
     ],
     "TableName": "MusicCollection",
     "KeySchema": [
         {
             "AttributeName": "Artist",
             "KeyType": "HASH"
         },
         {
             "AttributeName": "Title",
             "KeyType": "RANGE"
         }
     ],
     "ProvisionedThroughput": {
         "ReadCapacityUnits": 1,
         "WriteCapacityUnits": 1
     }
 }


Run create command referencing your previously created json file and using query to extract the table name. TABLE_NAME=$(aws dynamodb create-table --cli-input-json file://ch7/create-dynamo-db-table.json --query 'TableDescription.TableName' --output text)

Down

Delete table aws dynamodb delete-table --table-name $TABLE_NAME



Exercise 7.3 Add Items to DynamoDB Table
Up

Spin up a table from exercise 7.2, if needed
Add first item aws dynamodb put-item --table-name $TABLE_NAME --item '{"Artist": {"S": "Mystical Father"}, "Title": {"S": "Song for Elijah"}, "AlbumTitle": {"S": "Lovely Laura Likes Llamas"} }' --return-consumed-capacity TOTAL


Add second item aws dynamodb put-item --table-name $TABLE_NAME --item '{"Artist": {"S": "Steps in Springtime"}, "Title": {"S": "Allemande Left but will Return"}, "AlbumTitle": {"S": "Square dances for Round Rooms"} }' --return-consumed-capacity TOTAL


"Scan" your items to see them! aws dynamodb scan --table-name $TABLE_NAME

Down

Remove second item aws dynamodb delete-item --table-name $TABLE_NAME --key '{ "Artist": {"S": "Steps in Springtime"}, "Title": {"S": "Allemande Left but will Return"} }'


Remove first item aws dynamodb delete-item --table-name $TABLE_NAME --key '{ "Artist": {"S": "Mystical Father"}, "Title": {"S": "Song for Elijah"} }'


Delete table, if needed, by following 7.2 down instructions

Chapter 8 Application Deployment and Management
Exercise 8.1 Create an Elastic Beanstalk Environment, Exercise 8.2 Manage Application Versions with Elastic Beanstalk
Up

Set up variables used in later commandsENVIRONMENT_NAME="test-eb-env-$(openssl rand -hex 8)"
APPLICATION_NAME="test-eb-app-$(openssl rand -hex 8)"
TEMPLATE_NAME="test-eb-temp-$(openssl rand -hex 8)"
VERSION_LABEL="version-$(openssl rand -hex 16)"
CNAME_PREFIX="test-cname-$(openssl rand -hex 8)"
RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME="test-bucket-$(openssl rand -hex 18)"
BUNDLE_KEY=my-source-bundle.zip


Create new S3 bucketaws s3 mb "s3://${RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME}"


Create dummy source bundle

Create ch8 directorymkdir -p ch8


Create simple Flask application

Use ch8 as your current working directorycd ch8


Create and activate virtual environmentvirtualenv virt
source virt/bin/activate


Install flask and freeze requirementspip install flask==1.0.2
pip freeze > requirements.txt


Create application.py and paste following python code into file
from flask import Flask

# print a nice greeting.
def say_hello(username = "World"):
 return 'Hello %s!\n' % username

# some bits of text for the page.
header_text = '''
 \n EB Flask Test \n'''
instructions = '''
 Hint: This is a RESTful web service! Append a username
 to the URL (for example: /Thelonious) to say hello to
 someone specific.\n'''
home_link = 'Back\n'
footer_text = '\n'

# EB looks for an 'application' callable by default.
application = Flask(__name__)

# add a rule for the index page.
application.add_url_rule('/', 'index', (lambda: header_text +
 say_hello() + instructions + footer_text))

# add a rule when the page is accessed with a name appended to the site
# URL.
application.add_url_rule('/', 'hello', (lambda username:
 header_text + say_hello(username) + home_link + footer_text))

# run the app.
if __name__ == "__main__":
 # Setting debug to True enables debug output. This line should be
 # removed before deploying a production app.
 application.debug = True
 application.run()


Test by running python application.py


Initialize .elasticbeanstalk/* folder using awsebclieb init $APPLICATION_NAME -p python-3.6 --region us-east-1


Zip up ch8 folder into a bundlezip -r $BUNDLE_KEY ch8




Move dummy source bundle into newly created S3 bucketaws s3 cp $BUNDLE_KEY "s3://${RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME}/${BUNDLE_KEY}"


Create an Elastic Beanstalk applicationaws elasticbeanstalk create-application --application-name $APPLICATION_NAME


Create an Elastic Beanstalk application versionaws elasticbeanstalk create-application-version --application-name $APPLICATION_NAME --version-label $VERSION_LABEL --source-bundle S3Bucket=$RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME,S3Key=$BUNDLE_KEY


Create configuration template for applicationaws elasticbeanstalk create-configuration-template --application-name $APPLICATION_NAME --template-name $TEMPLATE_NAME --solution-stack-name "64bit Amazon Linux 2018.03 v2.7.3 running Python 3.6"

(Python solution stack selected because why not. Find more solution stacks by running aws elasticbeanstalk list-available-solution-stacks)
Create environmentaws elasticbeanstalk create-environment --cname-prefix $CNAME_PREFIX --application-name $APPLICATION_NAME --template-name $TEMPLATE_NAME --version-label $VERSION_LABEL --environment-name $ENVIRONMENT_NAME


Query every now and again until the environment is greenaws elasticbeanstalk describe-environments --environment-names $ENVIRONMENT_NAME


Deploy codecd ch8
eb deploy


Open application in browsereb open



Down

Terminate environmentaws elasticbeanstalk terminate-environment --environment-name $ENVIRONMENT_NAME


Delete configuration templateaws elasticbeanstalk delete-configuration-template --application-name $APPLICATION_NAME --template-name $TEMPLATE_NAME


Delete application versionaws elasticbeanstalk delete-application-version --application-name $APPLICATION_NAME --version-label $VERSION_LABEL


Delete applicationaws elasticbeanstalk delete-application --application-name $APPLICATION_NAME


Delete S3 bucketaws s3 rm "s3://${RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME}" --recursive
aws s3api delete-bucket --bucket "${RANDOM_BUCKET_NAME}"
